+My hypothesis is that a thirty minute minimum deliberation interval between consecutive decision gates will measurably reduce rubber-stamping because it forces the director to break context, return with fresh attention, and reconsider whether the council evidence actually supports advancing the proposal to the next expensive phase of work.
+My reasoning rests on my own experience chairing review panels where the worst decisions were always the ones made in a single sitting under deadline pressure, and where a forced overnight gap consistently surfaced objections that nobody had voiced while everyone was still anchored on the first framing presented.